make sure to create VM server on cloud with below port added in security group (AWS) and for GCP make sure to create firewall rules and attach tag to the VM-server.

-> -P - docker ephemeral ports ( predefined range 32768 to 61000 )
    -> -p - docker user defined ports ( custom range 8080 to 9090 )

-> Container Modes 

        -> docker container run --name c1 ubuntu:22.04

        -> Interactive / Foreground -it

            -> docker container run -it --name c2 ubuntu:22.04

        -> Detached / Background -dt (recommended)

            -> docker container run -dt --name c3 ubuntu:22.04

            -> Container always runs in background 

            -> docker container exec c3 cat /etc/os-release 
            -> docker container exec c3 ps -ef
            -> docker container exec -it c3 bash 

        -> docker container run 
        -> docker container stop c3
        -> docker container start c3
        -> docker container rm c3
        -> docker container rm -f c3 

    -> Setup Web Server Using Docker 

        -> docker container run -dt --name w1 nginx 
        -> docker container inspect w1
        -> curl 172.17.0.2

    
    -> To Access Containers Outside i.e internet we need to understand docker network

    -> Docker supports various network drivers, each designed for specific use case
        
        -> Host
        -> None
        -> Bridge
        
    -> Host: This driver removes network isolation between the container and the Docker host, 
        allowing them to share the hostâ€™s networking namespace.

        -> docker network ls 
        -> docker network inspect bridge
        -> docker container inspect w1

        -> docker network inspect host
        -> sudo ss -ntpl
        -> docker container run -dt --name w2 --network=host nginx 
        -> docker container ls -a
        -> docker network inspect host
        -> sudo ss -ntpl

        -> docker container exec w2 apt update -y

    -> None: This driver removes network access 

        -> docker network inspect none
        -> docker container run -dt --name w3 --network=none nginx 
        -> docker container exec w3 apt update -y

    -> Why Bridge Network 
        
        -> docker container run -dt --name w4 --network=host nginx 
        -> docker container ls -a
        -> docker container logs w4

    -> With Bridge Network

        -> docker container run -dt --name w5 nginx  
        -> docker container run -dt --name w6 nginx  
        -> docker container run -dt --name w7 nginx  
        -> docker container ls -a

        -> Using bridge network we can run multiple containers at same time, 
            but cannot be accessed outside via internet 

    -> Bridge: The default network driver for containers. 
        When a new container is run, it can be attached to this Bridge network.

    -> To Allow External Access To Containers using bridge, we can use Port Forwarding

-> This is the activity that makes a port inside a container 
            accessible to ports on the Docker host for external access.

        -> docker container run -dt --name w8 -p 8080:80 nginx  
        -> docker container run -dt --name w9 -p 8081:80 nginx  
        -> docker container run -dt --name w10 -p 8082:80 nginx  
        -> docker container ls -a

    -> -P - docker ephemeral ports ( predefined range 32768 to 61000 )
    -> -p - docker user defined ports ( custom range 8080 to 9090 )

        -> docker container run -dt --name w11 -P nginx  
        -> docker container run -dt --name w12 -P nginx  
        -> docker container run -dt --name w13 -P nginx  
        -> docker container ls -a


    -> docker container run -dt --name sonarqube -p 9000:9000 sonarqube

    -> docker container run -dt --name sonarqube --restart=always -p 9000:9000 sonarqube

    -> docker container run -dt --name w14 --restart=always -p 9090:80 nginx  

    -> docker container run -dt --name web-app -p 8080:80 nginx  

        -> In Above Container Deploy Login App 
            https://github.com/ravi2krishna/login-2519.git
        
        -> docker container exec -it web-app bash 
        -> apt update -y && apt install git -y
        -> git clone https://github.com/ravi2krishna/login-2519.git /var/www/html 

        -> In Docker Nginx Image Document root is /usr/share/nginx/html

            -> git clone https://github.com/ravi2krishna/login-2519.git /usr/share/nginx/html
            -> rm -r /usr/share/nginx/html/*
            -> git clone https://github.com/ravi2krishna/login-2519.git /usr/share/nginx/html

        -> exit 
        -> docker container rm -f web-app
        -> docker container run -dt --name web-app -p 8080:80 nginx  
        -> docker container ls -a
        -> Browse IP with port 

    -> NOTE: With above observation, we can say, when we remove container 
        all data associated with container is lost 

    -> By default containers are non-persistent in nature.

    -> Yes, containers are non-persistent (ephemeral) by default; 
        any data written to a container's writable layer is lost 
        when the container is stopped or deleted. 
        This design makes them lightweight, portable, and 
        easy to scale or replace, which is ideal for stateless applications. 

    -> Docker volumes is a mechanism for "persisting data" generated by Docker containers.  

    -> Docker volumes allow data to persist even when containers are deleted. 
